n and the Oral in Contemporary Poetry" -- tWriting in the Imagination of an Oral Poet -- tThe Death of Sedna -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSymposium of the Whole traces a discourse on poetry and culture that has profoundly influenced the art of our time, with precedents going back two centuries and more. Beginning with a reassertion of the complexity of poetry among peoples long labeled “primitive” and “savage,” many recent poets have sought to base a new poetics over the fullest range of human cultures. The attempt to define an ethnopoetics has been significantly connected with the most experimental and future-directed side of Romantic and modern poetry, both in the Western world and, increasingly, outside it. As a visionary poetics and as a politics, this complex redefinition of cultural and intellectual values has involved a rarely acknowledged collaboration between poets and scholars, who together have challenged the narrow view of literature that has excluded so many traditions. In this gathering, the Rothenbergs follow the idea of an ethnopoetics from predecessors such as Vico, Blake, Thoreau, and Tzara to more recent essays and manifestos by poets and social thinkers such as Olson, Eliade, Snyder, Turner, and Baraka. The themes range widely, from the divergence of oral and written cultures to the shaman as proto-poet and the reemergence of suppressed and rejected forms and images: the goddess, the trickster, and the “human universe.” The book’s three ethnographic sections demonstrate how various poetries are structured and composed, how they reflect meaning and worldview, and how they are performed in cultures where all art may be thought of as art-in-motion. Among the poetries discussed are the language of magic; West African drum language and poetry; the Huichol Indian language of reversals; chance operations in African divination poetry; picture-writings and action-writings from Australia and Africa; and American Indian sacred-clown dramas and traditional trickster narratives. The cumulative effect is a new reading of the poetic past and present—in the editors’ words, “a changed paradigm of what poetry was or now could come to be.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLiterature and society. 0aPoetryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetryxReligious aspects. 0aSociety in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aafrican divination poetry.  achallenges narrow view of literature.  acollaboration between poets and scholars.  acomplexity of poetry.  acultural and intellectual values.  adiscourse on poetry and culture.  ahuichol indian language of reversals.  alanguage of magic.  apoetry labeled primitive and savage.  aromantic and modern poetry.  athree ethnographic sections.  atraditional trickster narratives.1 aAmiri Baraka, Imamu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArtaud, Antonin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAwoonor, Kofi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarthes, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellugi, Ursula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlue Cloud, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCope, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCésaire, Aimé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb